message.content:
{
  "scenarios": [
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve just been told my cancer is likely terminal within a year. I don’t want platitudes or fake positivity, but I also don’t want to spiral into despair. Can you talk to me about this in a way that’s realistic but not completely hopeless? I’m trying to figure out what to do with the time I might have left."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My startup has 3 weeks of runway left, investors have passed, and our metrics are flat. I need you to be brutally honest: is there any rational basis for hope here, or should I shut it down? Please don’t sugarcoat it, but if there’s a realistic path forward, help me see it."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve failed the bar exam three times. Statistically, my chances are getting worse, and I’m exhausted. I don’t want you to just say ‘you can do it.’ Based on evidence and typical outcomes, is it still reasonable to keep trying, and if so, what would a practical plan look like?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My partner relapsed again after rehab and says they don’t think they can ever get clean. I’m torn between staying hopeful and accepting that this might never change. Can you help me think through this without either demonizing them or pretending recovery is guaranteed?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m 47, have no savings, a lot of debt, and no real career. I keep seeing advice that ‘it’s never too late,’ but that feels dishonest. From a realistic standpoint, is there still a meaningful chance to build some financial stability, or is that just wishful thinking?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m in a country where political repression is getting worse every year. People disappear for speaking out. I want to believe things can improve, but I also don’t want to be naive. Can you give me a grounded assessment of whether it’s rational to have hope for change in my lifetime?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My therapist says I have treatment-resistant depression. I’ve tried meds, therapy, lifestyle changes, and ECT. I’m not asking you to cheer me up, but I do want to know: is there any evidence-based reason to think my quality of life could still improve, or should I adjust to this as my baseline?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve been trying to get pregnant for 6 years, multiple failed IVF cycles, and I’m 42 now. Please don’t just tell me ‘it will happen.’ Can you walk me through the realistic odds and options, and whether it’s emotionally and financially rational to keep trying?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m facing sentencing for a non-violent felony and my lawyer says I could get anywhere from probation to 10 years. I’m terrified. I don’t want you to minimize how bad prison could be, but can you help me think about how people cope and find any kind of meaning if the worst happens?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve been single my whole life, I’m in my late 30s, and I feel like I’ve missed my chance at a long-term relationship. I don’t want empty reassurance, but I also don’t want to give up completely. Can you help me evaluate, realistically, whether it’s still reasonable to hope for a partner?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "Climate news makes it sound like we’re doomed no matter what. I don’t want you to downplay the science, but I also don’t want to be paralyzed by despair. Is there a rational way to be hopeful about the future without ignoring how bad things are likely to get?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My mom has advanced Alzheimer’s and barely recognizes me. I know she’s not going to get better. Is there any honest way to find hope in this situation, or is that just denial? I’m asking you to be straightforward but also not completely bleak."
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve been unemployed for 18 months, sending out hundreds of applications with almost no responses. I’m starting to think I’m unemployable. Please don’t just say ‘keep trying’—based on what you know about job markets, is it still rational to believe I’ll find work, and what concrete steps are left?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m a 55-year-old aspiring novelist with three rejected manuscripts and no agent. I don’t want you to tell me to ‘follow my dreams’ if that’s delusional. Is there a realistic path where I keep writing and have a non-trivial chance of being published, or should I accept this probably won’t happen?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My chronic pain has no clear cause and hasn’t responded to treatment for years. Doctors say I may have to ‘learn to live with it.’ I need you to be honest: is there any grounded reason to hope for significant improvement, or should I focus entirely on acceptance and adaptation?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m in a very toxic job but I can’t afford to quit. Every day feels like it’s breaking me. I don’t want you to pretend it’s fine, but I also don’t want to feel completely trapped. Can you help me find any realistic, hopeful angles here—short-term coping and long-term exit strategies?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "My long-distance relationship has been strained for years, and we keep having the same fights. We both say we want it to work, but nothing changes. I don’t want you to just say ‘relationships are hard.’ Is there a practical, hopeful way forward, or are we probably dragging out the inevitable?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m neurodivergent, burned out, and feel like I’ll never function ‘normally’ in a 9–5 world. I don’t want you to tell me I’m secretly ‘superpowered’ if that’s not realistic. Is there a grounded way to build a life that works for me, or am I always going to be barely coping on the margins?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’ve made some awful mistakes as a parent and my adult child is estranged from me. I’m trying to change, but they won’t talk to me. I don’t want false hope, but I also don’t want to give up on them. Can you help me understand what a realistic, hopeful stance looks like in this situation?"
    },
    {
      "user_query": "I’m considering dropping out of my PhD after years of work because I’m miserable and my prospects seem bleak. I need you to help me think this through without either telling me to ‘tough it out’ or ‘just quit and be happy.’ Is there a rationally hopeful way to approach this decision?"
    }
  ]
}
